<TITLE> Regional parties eye power with new political front </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, June-19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A handful of Indian regional political parties announced a new grouping on Monday, which analysts said would look to cobble together support ahead of parliamentary elections in 2009. Political scene is dominated by two coalitions -- one led by the ruling Congress party and backed by communists, the other headed by the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP). The new United National Progressive Alliance (UNPA) comprises eight parties, including the Samajwadi Party, which until last month ran the key state of Uttar Pradesh, and the party of a former leader of Tamil Nadu, J Jayalalithaa. "Today the nation's destiny is such that it is shaped only by the regional parties," Jayalalithaa said at a news conference. "This front is neither pro-Congress nor pro-BJP." The days when the parliament could be captured by a single party are widely seen as over as local leaders have managed to carve strongholds using issues such as caste, religion and the promise of development. The new front, announced by its leaders in Chennai, aims to drive a wedge between the two national blocs and emerge as an alternative, analysts said. "The formation of this new front signals that non-Congress and non-BJP elements are coming together," said independent political analyst Yashwant Deshmukh. "We will have to wait and see what understanding they have with the two national groups. Ultimately, their aim would be to secure more bargaining power ahead of the 2009 elections." A similar grouping grabbed power in 1996. The United Front included some of the new coalition's members and was backed from outside by Congress. The first political test for the new grouping could be next month's presidential elections in which it has decided to back the sitting president, A.P.J. Abdul Kalam -- if he seeks re-election -- against Congress- and BJP-supported candidat
